sentence-detokenized: CRICKET - LEICESTERSHIRE TAKE THE LEAD AFTER VICTORY.
West Indies all-rounder Phil Simmons scored four runs in 38 overs on Friday as Leicestershire beat Somerset by an innings and 39 runs in two days to take the lead in the county championship.

Their stay at the top could be short-lived, however, as defending champions Essex, Derbyshire and Surrey all came close to victory, while Kent made up ground in a rain-affected game against Nottinghamshire.

After Somerset had been bowled out for 83 at Grace Road on the opening morning, Leicestershire extended their first innings with 94 runs before scoring 296, with England's Andy Caddick hitting 83 for three.
Trailing 213, Somerset started the second inning solidly before Simmons stepped in and knocked them out for 174.
Essex, however, look confident of regaining their top spot after Nasser Hussain and Peter Such gave them a firm grip on the game against Yorkshire at Headingley.
Hussain, who was deemed surplus to England's one-day requirements, hit 158, his first league century of the season, as Essex reached 372 and took an 82-run first innings lead.
By the close, Yorkshire had taken a 37-run lead but off-spinner Such dashed their hopes, taking four for 24 in 48 balls, leaving them hanging on for 119 for five and praying for rain.
At the Oval, Surrey captain Chris Lewis, another man England have dropped, continued to silence his critics as he followed up his 45 fours on Thursday with 80 against Warwickshire on Friday.
He was well supported by England hopeful Mark Butcher, who made 70 as Surrey closed on 429 for the week, a lead of 234.
Derbyshire are chasing their first league title since 1936 as Worcestershire were 133 for five in the second innings and are still 100 runs away from avoiding an innings defeat.
Australia's Tom Moody scored six for 82, but Chris Adams scored 123 and Tim O'Gorman 109 to give Derbyshire a 471-run lead and 233 in the first innings.
After the frustration of the opening day of the match being badly affected by the weather, Kent switched up a gear and dismissed Nottinghamshire for 214.
A tough 84 from Paul Johnson kept them in it, but ex-England fast bowler Martin McCague scored four for 55.
Kent scored 108 for the three points.

SOCCER - SHEARER APPOINTED CAPTAIN OF THE ENGLISH NATIONAL TEAM.
The world's most expensive footballer, Alan Shearer, was appointed as the new England captain on Friday.
The 26-year-old, who arrived at Newcastle for £15 million ($23.4 million), will take over from Tony Adams and former captain David Platt at the European Championship in June.
Adams and Platt are both injured and will miss England's first World Cup qualifier against Moldova on Sunday.
Shearer will take up the captaincy on a trial basis, but new coach Glenn Hoddle has said he sees no reason why the former Blackburn and Southampton captain should not take the job.
"I'm sure there will be no problem, I'm sure Alan is the right man for the job," said Hoddle.
"There were three or four people who could have done it, but when I spoke to Alan, he was ready and keen.
"It's very difficult to draw 100 percent conclusions about something like this in four days...
but he knows how to behave, his teammates respect him and he is aware of the team's situation, even though he plays up front. "
Shearer's fellow Euro 96 striker Teddy Sheringham withdrew from the squad on Friday due to injury.
He is likely to be replaced by Shearer's Newcastle teammate Les Ferdinand.
FOOTBALL - ROMANIA BEAT LITHUANIA IN THE U21S MATCH.
Romania beat Lithuania 2-1 (1-1 at half-time) in the U21 European Football Championship on Friday.
FOOTBALL - ROTOR SUPPORTERS BANNED AFTER VOLGOGRAD VIOLENCE.

Rotor Volgograd will have to play their next home game behind closed gates after fans threw bottles and stones at Dynamo Moscow players in Saturday's 1-0 home defeat that ended Rotor's short-lived title run.
The head of the Russian league's disciplinary committee, Anatoly Gorokhovsky, announced on Friday that Rotor will play Lada Togliatti on 3 September in front of an empty stadium.
The club that knocked Manchester United out of last year's UEFA Cup has been fined $1000.
Despite the defeat, Rotor are in a good position with 11 games to go.
Three points behind Alania and two behind Dynamo Moscow, Volgograd have a one-match lead over the leaders and two over the Moscow club.
BOXING - ROBERTO DURAN FROM PANAMA FIGHTS THE SANDS OF TIME.
Panamanian boxing legend Roberto "Stone Hands" Duran will take to the ring on Saturday in another age-defying attempt to maintain his long career.
The 45-year-old Duran will take on the little-known Mexican Ariel Cruz (30) in a non-title super middleweight bout in Panama City.
The match, which is Duran's first home game in 10 years, is being billed as the "return of the legend" and Duran still talks as if he is in his prime.
"I would like to win a fifth title.
This match is to prepare myself.
I'm not retiring," Duran told Reuters.

However, those close to the boxer acknowledge that the man who has won titles in four different weight classes - lightweight, welterweight, junior middleweight and middleweight - is nearing the end of his career.
"In each of his matches, he is on the last frontier of his career.
If he loses on Saturday, it could devalue the position of one of the world's greatest boxers," said Ramon Manzanares, president of the Panamanian Boxing Federation.
Duran, whose record of 97-12 spans three decades, hopes to win a rematch against Puerto Rico's Hector "Macho" Camacho with a 10-round victory.
Camacho took a controversial points decision against the Panamanian in a title fight in Atlantic City in June.

TENNIS - TARANGO, O'BRIEN DOUBLE WIN UNDER THE LIGHTS.
Andre Agassi escaped disaster on Thursday, but Wimbledon finalists MaliVai Washington and Marcelo Rios were not so lucky at the US Open.
11th seed Washington could not repeat the Wimbledon miracle as they lost 6-3 6-4 6-4 5-7 3-6 6-3 to red-hot Alex O'Brien in a two-hour 51-minute battle on the Stadium court.
In the adjacent grandstand, Rios, seeded 10th, lost to another Wimbledon-bound player - bad boy Jeff Tarango.
The temperamental left-hander beat the Chilean 6-4 4-6 7-6 6-2.
The day's programme went smoothly, although sixth seeded former champion Agassi had to overcome a dangerous 3-6 0-4 deficit to win 18 of his last 19 games against India's Leander Paes.
But the night was for the up-and-comers.
Washington, who came back from 1-5 down in the third set against Todd Martin in the Wimbledon semi-finals, was preparing for another sensational comeback.
O'Brien, who won his first professional title in New Haven two weeks ago, served for the match at 5-4 in the third set before Washington fought back.
"I just kept saying to myself 'give yourself the best chance to win, keep fighting, maybe something will happen'," said the 26-year-old O'Brien, who is ranked 65th in the world.
"I kept my cool and was proud of myself - normally I would have folded up the tent and gone home."
A hard-serving O'Brien, the former U.S. University champion, threw down 17 aces to eventually defeat never-say-die Washington.
The fifth set was served until the sixth game when Washington, after saving a break point with a backhand shot down the line, hit a backhand shot to give O'Brien a 4-2 lead.
The Texan hit two aces to hold serve at 5-2 and then capitalized on her eighth match point for the win when Washington hit another backhand to net from 40-0.
"You just struggle and try to get him to play a little bit.
I think he was a little tense for a few moments," Washington said. "
But I think it served him well enough when he needed to. "

Tarango, whose tantrum at Wimbledon two years ago resulted in a $28,000 fine and a ban from this year's All-England Club tournament, argued with and taunted fans with calls during a lively two-hour, 24-minute tango in the stands with Rios.
The cheering fans supported the bewildered Chilean and booed the hulking American, who ate up all the attention.
"I am an emotional player," said Tarango, ranked 104th. "
I think I played very well tonight, very focused. "
The match came down to a third set tie-break, which the American won 7-5, much to the chagrin of the crowd.
"I like the public to boo me every day.
It fires me up and I play my best tennis," said Tarango.
"The best tennis I ever played in college was when the fraternities were spraying me with beer.
If tennis was like this every day, I think everyone would have a lot more fun. "
Rios did not appreciate Tarango's antics.
"He always complains too much," Rios said."
But I don't think that's the case.
I think I played very badly.
It was difficult to play at night.
The balls were going very fast.
I lost too many points that I never lose.
"I don't see the ball like I do during the day.
I play an American, so I play at night.
I did not feel comfortable on the pitch. "
At the end of the match, Tarango blew sarcastic kisses to the crowd and then shook his body in mock salute to the section cheering for Rios.
"I support their enthusiasm," Tarango said of the fans. "
At the same time, they are cheekily cheering against me.
After I won, I thought I'd give them a little dazzle. "
NFL AMERICAN FOOTBALL - RANDALL CUNNINGHAM RETIRES.
Randall Cunningham, the National Football League's all-time winningest quarterback and one of the most athletic players ever to play center, retired Thursday.
Cunningham spent his entire 11-year career with the Philadelphia Eagles.
Cunningham, a three-time Pro Bowl selection, had 4,482 yards on 677 carries.
"I want to thank the Eagles organization and the wonderful fans in Philadelphia for supporting me throughout my career," said Cunningham.
"Although I'm sad to leave, I'm looking forward to spending more time with my family and pursuing other interests that have been on the back burner for some time."
"Randall was one of the most exciting quarterbacks in NFL history," said Eagles owner Jeffrey Lurie. "
During his 11 years in Philadelphia, Randall was a cornerstone of the Eagles franchise and provided many great moments for Philadelphia fans and the NFL as a whole. "
A second-round pick in 1985, Cunningham completed 1,874 of 3,862 passes (55.7 percent) for 22,877 yards and 150 touchdowns.
Cunningham has already signed up to host.
